@{b} Usage @{ub}


It's very simple to use this program.  The  main window  is
splitted into several pages.  These pages are selectable at
the  top  of  the  window  or by pressing cursor left/right
keys to switch (sub-)page to the next or previous.

At program start UpRC tries to load a default contents file
saved previously  by the menu item  @{fg shine}Project/Save as default@{fg text}
if no other file to load was specified.

Starting UpRC from CLI there is now  the  "FILE"  parameter
available which allow you to load a readme file  at program
start.

Description of register pages:

  @{" About        " link usage_about} Informations about @{"myself" link author}.
  @{" Edit         " link usage_edit} Enter here the readme contents.
  @{" Settings     " link usage_settings} Global program setups.

Some functions are additionally available:

  @{" Menus        " link usage_menu} Functions available from menu.
  @{" Keyboard     " link usage_key} Extra provided shortcuts.

You can also drop workbench icons  over UpRC's main window.
UpRC  tries then to load that file as Aminet readme file or
convert it to a types list if it was a @{"TREE" link upload} file.

@Endnode
@Node usage_about "UpRC"
@Prev usage_menu
@Next usage_edit
@Toc usage

@{b} The about page @{ub}


This  page  has  no  functionality.  It  contains only some
informations about UpRC and @{"myself" link author}.

@Endnode
@Node usage_menu "UpRC"
@Prev usage_settings
@Next usage_key
@Toc usage

@{b} Functions available from program menu @{ub}


 @{i} Project menu @{ui}

  New -- Clears all readme related entries   (not the types
    list and the program settings).

  Open -- Read a new readme file in. You have to select the
    filename in the ASL-requester. If an corresponding Lha-
    archive exists, UpRC remember it's name too.

  Open default -- Reloads the default readme file.

  Save -- Write the entered data  as  readme to the current
    project file. An existing file will be overwritten.

  Save as -- Save the current entered data to  the file you
    have selected in the requester.

  Save as default -- Saves  the  current  entered  data  as
    default readme file (possibly also at program start).

  Preview -- Shows the current loaded project  as  complete
    readme file.

  Description -- This   item   is  only  available  if  the
    @{"Edit/Description" link usage_edit_description} page is active:

    Clear -- Remove the current description text.
    Load -- Load any text file (selectable by requester) as
      long description text.
    Insert -- Same as "Load",   but  the  text  to  load is
      inserted at the current cursor position.

  Save&Quit -- Saves the current readme data  (only  if any
    project name is given) and quit then.

  Quit -- UpRC exits.


 @{i} Options menu @{ui}

  Types -- This  menu  item  is related to the upload types
    list editor (@{"Edit/Types" link usage_edit_upload} page):

    Load -- Read a previously saved types list in.  It have
      the same function as "Restore"  at the @{"Upload types" link usage_edit_upload}
      page.
    Convert from -- Let you select an @{"Aminet TREE file" link upload}  to
      convert  it  into  UpRC's  own types list format.  To
      store this conversion you must use the @{fg shine}save@{fg text} button on
      the @{"types editor" link usage_edit_upload} page.
    Use selected -- Uses the current selected  upload  type
      and class as upload type for the current readme.
    Save -- Save the current types list to disk as the same
      function "Save" at the @{"Upload types" link usage_edit_upload} page do.

  Windows -- Will handle the intuition part  of  UpRC  main
    and preview windows:

    Reset to saved -- Sets the windows positions/dimensions
      to the last saved values.
    Snapshot -- Saves       the       current       windows
      dimensions/positions to the ".config" file.

  Settings -- Handles  the  setup  storage file used by the
      @{"Settings" link usage_settings} page.

    Restore -- Load the last saved settings.
    Save -- Save  the  current  settings  to  the ".config"
      file (including the UpRC current window dimensions).

@Endnode

@Node usage_key "UpRC"
@Next usage_about
@Prev usage_menu
@Toc usage

@{b} Provided keyboard shortcuts (not related to gadgets) @{ub}


@{u}General:@{uu}

TAB-Cycling  is  available at all pages  with more than one
string/integer gadget on it.

Hitting  the  <TAB>-key  at  the  readme  edit  pages  will
activate the first  string/textfield  gadget at the current
page. At the  edit recommended page you can open the upload
type selecting window by hitting  <TAB>-/<RETURN>-key  with
the <SHIFT>-key together, if any string gadget is active.


@{u}At UpRC main window:@{uu}

@{i} Esc @{ui}
Quits UpRC immediatly same as you click on the main windows
close gadget.

@{i} Cursor right @{ui}
Switches to the next program page or to the next sub-page.

@{i} Cursor left @{ui}
Switches to the previous page or sub-page.

@{i} TAB @{ui}
Only available at the edit readme data pages:  The  TAB-key
will activate the first string gadget  at the current page.
The  TAB-Cycling  includes  also  opening  the  type select
windows available at the @{"Edit recommended" link usage_edit_required} page.


@{u}At upload types selecting windows:@{uu}

@{i} Esc @{ui}
Cancels the selection in the same way you press  the @{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}
button.

@{i} Return @{ui}
Selects the current (highlighted) entry  (same as you press
the @{fg shine}Use@{fg text} button).

@{i} Cursor up @{ui}
Highlight the previous entry (if possible) in the list.

@{i} Cursor down @{ui}
Highlight the following entry (if possible) in the list.


@{u}At requirements editor:@{uu}

@{i} Esc @{ui}
Cancels the requirements editor

@{i} Cursor up/down@{ui}
Highlight  the  previous/next  entry  from the requirements
list.

@{i} Return @{ui}

Mark the current highlighted entry as selected  and  append
it  to  the  selection  list  or if it exist there already,
unselect it.

@Endnode

@Node usage_edit "UpRC"
@Prev usage_about
@Next usage_settings
@Toc main

@{b} Usage of the "Edit" page @{ub}


This page is splitted again into four pages named:

  @{" Recommended  " link usage_edit_required} Enter the mainly recommended entries.
  @{" Additional   " link usage_edit_additional} Type here the additional entries.
  @{" Description  " link usage_edit_description} Edit the long description.
  @{" Upload types " link usage_edit_upload} Change/add the upload directory (type).

If you're not sure about the format of Aminet readme files,
read the @{"About readme files" link readme} chapter now.

@Endnode

@Node usage_edit_required "UpRC"
@Prev usage_edit_upload
@Next usage_edit_additional
@Toc usage_edit

@{b} Usage of the "Edit - Recommended" page @{ub}


You have to enter in the text input gadgets the recommended
information  about  the  archive  to  upload   like   short
description,  name of uploader  and the name of the author.
The real required entry for  Aminet  readmes  is  only  the
"Short:" description as first line.

To  select  the upload type  (Aminet directory)  press  the
@{fg shine}type@{fg text}  button  and select the requested entry  in the window
and do the same in the window opened after that.  The @{fg shine}class@{fg text}
button let you only choose a subdirectory  if  a legal type
entry was selected.

If you select @{fg shine}Author is Uploader@{fg text},  the author field will be
also written as uploader field automatically.

Note:  All  entries at this page are required  for creating
the Aminet archive readme file but  UpRC  didn't  check the
validity of the entered data!

If  you  have no idea  about  the contents of Aminet readme
files, first read @{"this" link readme} chapter.

@Endnode

@Node usage_edit_additional "UpRC"
@Prev usage_edit_required
@Next usage_edit_description
@Toc usage_edit

@{b} Usage of the "Edit - Additional" page @{ub}


Here  you  may  enter some additional information about the
archive  to upload  (german short description,  replacement
information, requirements and version).

If  you  leave  any  field  empty it will not appear in the
readme file later.

You  can  also  build  the  @{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}  string  using the
@{"Requester" link usage_edit_requirements} opened after clicking the @{fg shine}browse@{fg text} button.

If  you  have no idea  about  the contents of Aminet readme
files, first read @{"this" link readme} chapter.

@Endnode

@Node usage_edit_description "UpRC"
@Prev usage_edit_additional
@Next usage_edit_upload
@Toc usage_edit

@{b} Usage of the "Edit - Description" page @{ub}


You can enter here  some additional informations about your
archive  to  upload.  This  text  input  field  isn't  very
configurable so you must include linfeeds by hand (pressing
"RETURN"). Remember: Every line shouldn't have more than 80
characters for a better looking!

You  should  always  include  one  or more linefeeds (empty
lines)  at the top  of the long description text for better
looking in the result. UpRC can't handle it correctly.

There are options  to clear,  load  and  insert  text  from
program   @{"menu" link usage_menu}   "Project/Description",   which  is   only
available if this page is active.

If  you  have no idea  about  the contents of Aminet readme
files, first read @{"this" link readme} chapter.

@Endnode
@Node usage_edit_upload "UpRC"
@Prev usage_edit_description
@Next usage_edit_required
@Toc usage

@{b} Usage of the "Upload types" page @{ub}


At  this  page, its possible to edit the upload types list.
In  the  left  listview  are  all   (current)  main  upload
directories  available  and  by  clicking any entry in this
list in the right listview all corresponding subdirectories
are shown.

This page is a little bit obsolete, because UpRC is able to
load the types list from a @{"TREE" link upload} file.

@{fg shine}New@{fg text} will create a new entry in the the types/class list and
you have to enter the name of the entry to create.   @{fg shine}Remove@{fg text}
remove the current selected entry.

The  @{fg shine}Save@{fg text}  button will save the complete list forever.  The
@{fg shine}Restore@{fg text} button will load the last saved list again.

The upload type is very important,  because  many  software
at  the  Aminet  will appear in wrong directories and never
found by the user. So take a look at the @{"TREE" link upload} file to show
the descriptions of every upload (sub-)directory taken from
Aminet.
                                         
From the @{"menu" link usage_menu} item "Options/Types/Convert from..." or from
the  @{fg shine}Convert@{fg text}  button  you  are able to convert Aminet @{"TREE" link upload}
files to the internal types list format.

If  you  have no idea  about  the contents of Aminet readme
files, first read @{"this" link readme} chapter.

@Endnode
@Node usage_settings "UpRC"
@Prev usage_edit
@Next usage_menu
@Toc usage

@{b} Usage of the "Settings" page @{ub}


Here you can enter some global program settings:

@{fg shine}Font@{fg text}
    You may select here the  (fixed width sized)  font  for
    use   in  the  textfield.gadget  display.   Default  is
    topaz.font, size 8.

@{fg shine}Lha exe@{fg text}
    Filename and location  of your Lha archiver executable.
    It's required for writing archive contents.  Make  sure
    you pass here the right path and filename of your  Lha-
    archiver,  because  UpRC ca'nt detect  if anything goes
    wrong executing the entered program.

@{fg shine}Archive contents@{fg text}
    Switches the writing of archive contents on  (hook)  or
    off.  This feature will write also some text not needed
    for readme files.  Have a look at the resulting readme!
    Switch off  this option  if you'll create a readme  for
    *.mpeg, *.jpg or *.lzx files.

@{fg shine}Save settings on exit@{fg text}
    If selected,  the settings will be saved if the program
    exit.

@{fg shine}Sort requirements@{fg text}
    Option for the @{"requirements editor" link usage_edit_requirements}: If activated,  the
    available   requirements  entries  will  be  sorted  in
    alphabetical order.

@{fg shine}Default at startup@{fg text}
    This switch enables loading  the default readme file at
    program start.

@{fg shine}Store archive file@{fg text}
    Not yet implemented.

@{fg shine}Learn requirements@{fg text}
    Option for the @{"requirements editor" link usage_edit_requirements}: If activated,  all
    already  entered requirements entries  (unknown to UpRC
    at this time)  will  be  added to the available entries
    list.

@{fg shine}Check entries@{fg text}
    @{bg text}@{fg back}Recommended:@{fg text}@{bg back}  Recommended  entries  for  Aminet  upload
    readme appear also if you have'nt entered some data for
    it.
    @{bg text}@{fg back}Requested by Aminet:@{fg text}@{bg back}  Only the "Short" entry appears in
    the readme file.  All other entries are not written, if
    no related datas are present.
    @{bg text}@{fg back}All:@{fg text}@{bg back} UpRC checks if all entries are present  and report
    an error if one of them misses.
    @{bg text}@{fg back}None:@{fg text}@{bg back} No entry will be checked.

@{fg shine}Write at offset@{fg text}
    This slider sets the row where starts the header texts
    (only).  The  header  description  texts  itself (like
    "Short", "Author", ...) are not affected.

Saving  and  loading  settings  is  only possible using the
@{"menu" link usage_menu} items "Options/Settings/Restore" and ".../Save".

@Endnode
@Node usage_edit_requirements "UpRC"
@Next usage_edit_additional
@Prev usage_edit_additional
@Toc usage

@{b} Usage of the Requirements editor @{ub}


This window allows  you  to  construct  the  "requirements"
entry for your readme file.

Doubleclicking  on  a  requiremnts entry in the global list
will select it or unselect it if it already exist.

You  can  also  scroll through the global requirements list
via  cursor up/down keys and select/unselect items with the
return key.

Note: Only  comma  separators  for every requirements entry
      are handled by UpRC!

@{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text}
    This  list  contains  all  known  requirements entries.
    Doubleklicking  one entry will select it,  or  unselect
    if it was allready selected.

@{fg shine}Selected@{fg text}
    Shows the list of selected entries. If you click on one
    entry  in  this  list,   it   will   selected   in  the
    @{fg shine}Requirements@{fg text} list.

@{fg shine}Require@{fg text}
    This  line  shows  the current selected entry.  You can
    change it by typing new text.

@{fg shine}New@{fg text}
    Add  a  new (empty) entry to the global requirements
    list.

@{fg shine}Remove@{fg text}
    Remove  the  current  selected  entry  from  the global
    requirements list.

@{fg shine}(Un)Select@{fg text}
    Add the current selected  entry  to  your  requirements
    description.

@{fg shine}Clear@{fg text}
    Clears  the  selected  requirements  entries  (not  the
    global list!).

@{fg shine}Ok@{fg text}
    Take the current settings as requirements string.

@{fg shine}Cancel@{fg text}
    Nothing changes, but the window closes. ;)


@Endnode
@Node limitations "UpRC"
@Next history
@Prev upload
@Toc main

@{b} Limitations of UpRC software @{ub}


* UpRC ca'nt handle some cases of archive contents listings
  in the long description.   If in the description  appears
  a line containing more than nineteen "=" chars,  the text
  behind that line will be truncated.

* There are  some older readme files  (mainly  as  part  of
  scene demo uploads with an  "Action:"  field  in the file
  header.  This entry is unknown to UpRC but UpRC reports a
  warning if this appears.

* UpRC  uses  the  Lha  executable  to generate the archive
  contents listing. This output will be completely appended
  at the long description text with all possible (and maybe
  unwanted) texts.

* The upload archive  and readme file must stay in the same
  directory and must have the same name  (naturally  except
  the suffix) to use  in  UpRC  software.  But this is'nt a
  real   limitation   because   Aminet   request  the  same
  restriction.

* No online help integrated. No ARexx® port.

* uprc.library  and  (later)  aminetrd.library  too  are'nt
  downwards compatible, so you *must* use the whole library
  version distributed within the related UpRC archive!

* All configuration setups will be saved into files present
  in  the  PROGDIR:config  drawer.   No  tooltype  settings
  supported. This may or may not change in the future.

* Config file format is'nt downwards compatible too.  Do'nt
  use other savefiles except created by this UpRC version!

* UpRC is a little bit static,  if  the  Aminet readme file
  format change in the future.  In that case you've to wait
  for an update which handles that changes.

* UpRC ignores unknown header entries  completely. This may
  change in the future.

@Endnode
@Node history "UpRC"
@Next main
@Prev limitations
@Toc main

@{b} History @{ub}

-----------------------------------------------------------
v2.2rev1          29.09.2000
        - Change: Moved   software  state  of  UpRC  to  be
                  FREEWARE!    Keyfiles    are   completely
                  obsolete.
        - Change: Online help feature removed.
        - Change: Reading report removed.
        - Change: "About" page redisigned and simplified.
        - Change: Reading    report    feature   completely
                  removed.
        - Change: Program icon adapted to OS3.5 style.
        - Change: Rework of aminetrd.library.
-----------------------------------------------------------
V2.1              01.10.1999
        - Change: UpRC    uses   now   my   new   (changed)
                  aminetrd.library      in     place     of
                  uprc.library; aminetrd.library  is a part
                  of the uprc archive.  This  was  done for
                  future  compatibility  with  other aminet
                  readme related software.
        - Add:    UpRC is now installable  as project icons
                  default-tool   entry  (reading  WorkBench
                  arguments).
-----------------------------------------------------------
V2.0b             06.08.1999
