@Next reading
@Toc main

@{b} About upload types @{ub}


The upload types are the same as the directories on Aminet,
where you can place your software in.  This will be done by
the Aminet  providers  itself.   You have only  to give the
information  of  the  requested  location for your uploaded
software in the @{fg shine}Type@{fg text} field of the readme file.

UpRC1.3+ is able to read  informations  about  Aminet types
from the provided  "TREE"  files  available  directly  from
Aminet ftp servers  (very actual)  or  from Aminet CD-ROM's
also.   Use the version from the /aminet directory, not the
tree   file  placed  in  /aminet/info directory!  They  are
different.

Reading the types list from that TREE file contains a small
limitation:  At  the  @{fg shine}Upload types@{fg text}  page you have to remove
The "info" entry  from the Type list.   This isn't a Aminet
directory to place uploads in!  Beginning  from  V1.4  UpRC
removes this entry automatically.

@Endnode

@Node reading "UpRC"
@Prev upload
@Next limitations
@Toc main

@{b} Some informations about reading readmes @{ub}


UpRC is able to read  any existing Aminet readme file  that
belongs to the minority restriction requested by Aminet for
readme files.  Only the  "Short:"  entry must be present as
the first line in the file.

But there are some limitations for completely reading those
files.  Between the readme entries  ("Short:", "Uploader:",
"Author:", etc.)  are no empty lines allowed.  Behind  that
header  a  blank  line  must be inserted to detect the long
description text. UpRC recognize the Archive contents block
by a line with at minimum 19 "=" chars.  Most  of uploaders
write here  "===== ... === Archive contents === ... =====".
This is also done by UpRC.  If  there  is  any other option
recommended, mail it to @{"me" link author}.

The reading report will show you all problems about reading
the  current  readme  file  (unknown readme header entries, 
wrong readme file format). 

@Endnode
